search:Security Patterns:.net mvc securi.content:
- Use `dotnet new mvc -n SecureApp` to create a new secure MVC project.
- Update your project file (.csproj) to target the latest LTS version of .NET Core or .NET 6+.
- Implement authentication using Identity by running `dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Identity.EntityFrameworkCore`.
- Configure cookie options in `Startup.cs`:
  ```csharp
  services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options =>
  {
      options.SlidingExpiration = false;
      options.ExpireTimeSpan = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30);
      options.Cookie.HttpOnly = true;
  });
  ```
- Use HTTPS by setting `<UseHttpsRedirection>true</UseHttpsRedirection>` in `Startup.cs`.
- Implement authorization using `[Authorize]` and `[Roles]` attributes on controllers or actions.
- Regularly update packages to the latest versions using `dotnet upgrade tool`.
- Enable dependency injection for services that require configuration, e.g., `services.AddScoped<IMyService, MyService>()`.
- Use middleware for common tasks like logging and error handling:
  ```csharp
  app.UseRouting();
  app.UseAuthentication();
  app.UseAuthorization();
  app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
  {
      endpoints.MapControllerRoute(
          name: "default",
          pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
  });
  ```
- Implement input validation using data annotations or custom validators.
- Use the OWASP cheat sheet for secure coding guidelines and best practices.
